# What to figure out before designing sound

Always gather or infer the following:

## Product context
- product type
- target platform: web, iOS, Android, desktop, wearable, game, kiosk, automotive, spatial
- user environment: quiet office, public transit, warehouse, living room, outdoors, accessibility-heavy context
- whether the product is productivity, consumer, finance, health, entertainment, education, accessibility, or safety-critical

## Interaction context
- trigger event
- user goal at that moment
- what uncertainty the sound resolves
- event frequency
- event severity
- whether it is user-initiated or system-initiated
- whether it occurs once, repeatedly, or in bursts
- whether it needs a start, progress, and end cue

## Multimodal context
- associated animation/motion
- haptic availability
- existing visual affordances
- text labels or state messages
- whether spoken content or screen readers may be active

## Brand context
- desired adjectives: calm, premium, playful, precise, trustworthy, warm, clinical, mechanical, spatial, futuristic, human
- what the brand should never sound like
- whether the product wants recognizability or invisibility

## Technical context
- file format constraints
- latency constraints
- implementation target
- whether audio must duck other content
- whether system-owned notification channels exist
- whether the sound needs multiple variants

If any of this is missing, ask concise high-value questions. If the user does not answer, state assumptions and proceed.

