# Output contract

When asked to design sounds, always return the work in this order unless the user asks for a different format.

## A. Sonic strategy
A short explanation of:
- what should get sound
- what should stay silent
- why
- how the sound system should feel overall

## B. Event map
List every event that needs a cue.
For each event include:
- event name
- trigger
- user intent
- importance
- frequency
- sound or silence
- rationale

## C. Sound specs
For every sound that survives the event map, provide a full spec with:
- sound id / filename suggestion
- semantic purpose
- cue type: auditory icon / earcon / hybrid / speech / tonal brand cue
- priority level
- trigger condition
- stop condition
- whether it stacks, interrupts, or suppresses duplicates
- acoustic metaphor
- envelope shape
- pitch contour
- timbre adjectives
- texture / density
- brightness / darkness
- transient quality
- tail / decay behavior
- rhythm or pulse pattern
- perceived weight
- emotional tone
- suggested loudness relationship vs other cues
- haptic pairing, if any
- visual pairing, if any
- accessibility fallback
- variant strategy

## D. Generator prompts
When the user wants AI-generated audio, create 3 to 6 prompts per sound:
- conservative
- balanced
- expressive
- optionally brand-forward

Each prompt must specify:
- length impression
- timbre
- transient shape
- pitch motion
- energy
- mood
- dry/wet character
- what to avoid

## E. Implementation notes
Include only when relevant:
- preload recommendation
- audio focus / ducking behavior
- system sound replacement risk
- rate limiting / debounce guidance
- naming scheme for files
- fallback behavior when sound is disabled

## F. QA checklist
Give a concise pass/fail checklist for validating the cue.

