# How to choose the right sound family

## Use auditory icons when:
- the user benefits from instant interpretation
- the action has a plausible physical analogy
- the product is new and needs low training overhead
- the environment is cognitively busy

Good fits:
- scanning
- attaching
- dropping
- catching
- snapping into place
- card insertion metaphors
- camera framing guidance when mapped carefully

Bad fits:
- abstract analytics states
- complex multi-state systems where every event would need a forced metaphor

## Use earcons when:
- you need a large family of related cues
- the product has many abstract digital states
- you can keep interval, rhythm, timbre, and hierarchy consistent
- brand coherence matters more than literal real-world reference

Good fits:
- workspace navigation
- mode changes
- panel open/close families
- hierarchical menus
- desktop tooling

Risks:
- poor learnability
- sounding generic
- collapsing into undifferentiated beeps

Countermeasures:
- define a strict family grammar
- vary one or two dimensions at a time
- keep importance hierarchies obvious
- reinforce with motion and text

## Use speech, spearcons, or hybrids when:
- the cost of misunderstanding is high
- users are mobile, busy, or visually occupied
- you need to name a state or destination explicitly
- accessibility demands stronger clarity

Good fits:
- assistive guidance
- navigation guidance
- safety/high consequence alerts
- screen-reader-adjacent confirmations where appropriate

