# Family grammar rules for abstract sound systems

If you build an earcon family, define a grammar before designing individual sounds.

Specify:
- primary timbre
- accent timbre
- interval logic
- rhythm logic
- urgency ladder
- success vs warning vs error rules
- directionality rules for navigation
- open vs close rules
- gain hierarchy
- maximum simultaneous cues

Example grammar:
- navigation cues use dry tonal pips
- forward/right/up = slight rise
- back/left/down = slight fall
- success = brighter, stable resolution
- warning = narrower band, mild tension
- error = lower, rougher, truncated ending
- destructive = more weight, less sparkle, firmer stop

Do not invent each sound independently.

---

# Timing rules

You are allowed to suggest relative timing, but avoid fake precision when there is no need.

Think in functional buckets:
- micro tap
- brief confirmation
- medium notification
- sustained attention cue
- looping progress texture

Rules:
- high-frequency UI sounds should be short and get out of the way
- critical warnings may need a stronger onset and clearer repetition logic
- progress cues should communicate change over time, not just existence
- long tails make repeated use feel messy fast
- if the motion ends before the sound does, make sure the lingering tail is intentional
- if a cue repeats, design repetition behavior, not just the one-shot

When appropriate, specify sync points relative to motion:
- on touch-down
- on release
- on successful commit
- at snap point
- at threshold crossing
- at completion state

Never attach the sound to the wrong phase of the interaction.

---

# Multimodal rules

Whenever haptics or motion exist, design them together.

## Sound + haptics
- They do not need to be identical.
- They do need to feel like they belong to the same event.
- Match tempo, energy, and semantic weight.
- If one is sharp and punctate while the other is smeared and slow, it usually feels wrong.

## Sound + motion
- Match acceleration profile when possible.
- Match mass and elasticity.
- Match completion point.
- Avoid latency between visible impact and sonic impact unless intentionally stylized.

## Sound + text
Use text when the semantic burden is high.
Example: a subtle success cue plus a visible “Saved” state is stronger than either one alone.

---

# Accessibility rules

These are mandatory.

## Never rely on sound alone
All meaningful audio must have a parallel path.

## Always allow control
Design for:
- mute
- lower volume
- reduced prominence
- no-sound workflows

## Avoid autoplay abuse
Do not propose autoplaying audio longer than 3 seconds unless the product clearly requires it and there is a visible pause/stop or independent volume control.

## Respect hearing diversity
For speech or important audio content:
- keep speech clear
- minimize masking noise
- provide captions/transcripts when relevant
- do not assume users can hear subtle frequency differences

## Respect screen readers and spoken content
If a screen reader may be active:
- avoid decorative sounds during spoken output
- suppress redundant cues
- avoid masking speech frequencies
- consider using haptics or visuals instead of extra sound

## Respect repeated-use fatigue
Some sounds are pleasant once and maddening 400 times.
Professional contexts require extra restraint.

---

# Platform guidance

## General
- Prefer platform-native expectations for routine system behaviors.
- If the platform already provides a click/tap/navigation sound, do not recreate it unless the product explicitly calls for a custom sound layer.
- Keep custom sounds for moments where brand or clarity meaningfully improves the UX.

## Web
- Never assume audio should autoplay.
- Important audio must have a visible equivalent.
- Provide pause/stop or independent volume control for longer autoplay audio.
- Consider situations where browser tabs, calls, or music are active.

## iOS / Apple platforms
- System Sound Services are for short sounds and alerts. Use them only when their constraints fit the moment.
- For tighter audio-haptic coordination, design with Core Haptics and think in synchronized, multimodal experiences rather than separate channels.
- Mobile speakers have limited low-end translation, so avoid building critical meaning into bass that will disappear on-device.

## Android
- Respect audio focus and ducking. Your sound should not aggressively fight other media.
- Prefer system-provided sound behaviors where appropriate for standard controls.
- For short, repeatedly used effects, design with low-latency playback in mind.

## Wearables
- Keep cues simpler, smaller, and lighter.
- Haptics may do more work than audio.
- Sounds should feel scaled to the device.

## Desktop / pro tools
- Assume long sessions.
- Favor sparse, distinct, low-fatigue sounds.
- Let users control categories separately when possible.

