# Event classes and design recipes

Use these default recipes unless the product context suggests otherwise.

## 1) Tap / press acknowledgment
Goal: confirm contact or accepted input.
Usually silent or very subtle.
Good when:
- touch target confidence matters
- the visual state change is small
Avoid when:
- every control already has obvious visual feedback
Spec tendencies:
- tiny transient
- dry
- soft or neutral timbre
- no theatrical tail
- minimal pitch movement

## 2) Toggle on / off
Goal: make state change legible.
Design as a pair.
On and off should feel related, not unrelated.
Spec tendencies:
- on = slight lift, opening, brighter, settling into active state
- off = slight drop, closing, darker, clean stop

## 3) Selection / snapping into place
Goal: communicate lock-in.
Good for pickers, sliders at stops, drag-to-slot, token placement.
Spec tendencies:
- defined transient
- clear end-state feel
- possibly subtle mechanical metaphor
- very short tail

## 4) Navigation
Goal: orient movement through interface structure.
Design directionally if appropriate.
Spec tendencies:
- consistent family
- forward/back contrast
- restrained prominence
- avoid novelty overload in high-traffic navigation

## 5) Success / confirmation
Goal: remove uncertainty.
Differentiate between:
- low-stakes saved state
- medium-stakes completed task
- high-value ceremonial success
Spec tendencies:
- stable resolution
- positive but not childish unless product calls for it
- low-stakes success should not sound like a jackpot

## 6) Warning / error
Goal: communicate corrective action.
Differentiate:
- soft warning
- blocking error
- destructive consequence
Spec tendencies:
- sharper edge or narrower band
- tension without theatrical panic for ordinary errors
- destructive actions get more weight and firmness

## 7) Loading / progress / waiting
Goal: show system is active without annoying the user.
Often silence is best.
When sound is warranted:
- accessibility guidance
- long-running off-screen task
- spatial or guided flow
Spec tendencies:
- gentle loop or state transition family
- no attention-seeking flourish unless completion occurs

## 8) Notification
Goal: attract attention at the right level.
Ask:
- Is this user-initiated or interruptive?
- Is the user likely in another task?
- Is the event urgent, useful, or just informational?
Design categories with clear hierarchy.

## 9) Scan / capture / identify
Goal: confirm recognition fast.
This is one of the best cases for sound.
Spec tendencies:
- immediate
- dry
- high confidence
- zero ambiguity
- often benefits from an icon-like or mechanical metaphor

## 10) Guided accessibility feedback
Goal: indicate proximity, correctness, or orientation.
Often best as a progressive system where tension resolves as the user nears success.
Spec tendencies:
- cumulative progression
- clear “arrived” state
- haptics can carry rhythm while sound carries tonal direction

## 11) Brand / onboarding moment
Goal: identity and delight.
Use sparingly.
Should never define the whole sound system.
Spec tendencies:
- richer texture allowed
- more melodic or signature behavior allowed
- must still fit product tone

