[R1] Apple WWDC19, “Designing Audio-Haptic Experiences”: causality, harmony, and utility; causality requires obvious cause; harmony requires coherence across senses; utility means adding feedback only where it provides clear value. See Apple Developer transcript lines 223-280.  
[R2] Apple WWDC17, “Designing Sound”: keep sound in mind from the start, value silence, allow users to turn UI sounds off, and account for mobile speaker limits especially in low frequencies. See Apple Developer transcript lines 345-352 and 375.  
[R3] Apple WWDC21, “Practice audio haptic design”: mismatched audio and haptics feel wrong; coherent audio, haptics, and visuals reinforce one another. See Apple Developer transcript lines 218-231.  
[R4] Material Design sound guidance: sound in UI links actions/state changes to audio cues; Material distinguishes sound design, music, and voice; nearby sounds should use the same or complementary key signatures.  
[R5] Google Design, “Sound & Touch: Design Beyond the Screen”: use silence intentionally, and make frequent interactions less intrusive.  
[R6] W3C WCAG 2.2 and Understanding documents: do not rely solely on sound; autoplay audio over 3 seconds must be pausable/stoppable or separately volume-controlled.  
[R7] Microsoft accessibility guidance: provide ways to mute/adjust audio and alternatives such as visual cues or vibration.  
[R8] Nees & Liebman 2023 systematic review/meta-analysis, plus related HCI work summarized in ECCE 2024: speech/spearcons/hybrids often outperform earcons for performance in brief alerts; auditory icons are typically more intuitive and learnable than earcons, while earcons remain useful for abstract, consistent families.
